Q1: Is there a correlation between employability test and salary?

#
# Need to first drop the NAs
# Test for correlation
wo.NA = dt %>% filter(!is.na(etest_p) & !is.na(salary))
cor(wo.NA$etest_p, wo.NA$salary)
## [1] 0.1783073
wo.NA %>% ggplot(mapping=aes(x=etest_p, y=salary))+geom_point()+geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The cor output gives us the correlation between employability test and salary, which is 0.1783073. And thus we can see that there is a weak positive correlation between employability test and salary.

Q2: Are there any significant differences of salaries between different fields of undergraduate research?

wo.NA2 = dt %>% filter(!is.na(degree_t) & !is.na(salary))
wo.NA2 %>% ggplot(mapping=aes(x=degree_t, y=salary))+geom_boxplot()+geom_point(data=wo.NA2 %>% group_by(degree_t) %>% summarise(deg.mean = mean(salary)) %>% ungroup(), mapping=aes(x=degree_t, y=deg.mean, color='red'))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

TukeyHSD(aov(salary~degree_t, data=wo.NA2))
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = salary ~ degree_t, data = wo.NA2)
## 
## $degree_t
##                         diff        lwr       upr     p adj
## Others-Comm&Mgmt    1772.549 -98763.204 102308.30 0.9990394
## Sci&Tech-Comm&Mgmt 35982.305  -4604.955  76569.57 0.0935045
## Sci&Tech-Others    34209.756 -69762.081 138181.59 0.7164123

From the boxplot above, we can assume that there is not a significant differences of salaries between different fields of undergraduate research. And we propose our Null and Alternative Hypotheses:

  • Null Hypothesis \(H_{0, i, j}\): There is no difference in mean between two groups of different field of undergraduate research for any two groups \({i, j}\)
  • Alternative Hypothesis \(H_{A, i, j}\): There is at least one group with mean significantly different from another group.

We can see from the Tukey HSD test above that all of these adjusted p-values are larger than 5%, which means that we reject our alternative hypothesis, and there isnt a significant difference in salary between different field of study.

#
# Q4
ggplot(data=dt, mapping=aes(x=degree_p, y=etest_p, color=degree_t))+geom_point()+geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

without.degree_t = lm(etest_p~degree_p, data=dt)
with.degree_t = lm(etest_p~degree_p+degree_t, data=dt)
smr.with.degree_t = summary(with.degree_t)
anova.degree_t = anova(without.degree_t, with.degree_t)
smr.with.degree_t
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = etest_p ~ degree_p + degree_t, data = dt)

## F-statistic: 3.925 on 3 and 211 DF,  p-value: 0.009368
anova.degree_t[2, 6]
## [1] 0.759515

From the plot above, we can see that degree percentage might have a weak positive relationship with employability test score, while the field of research does not have a large impact on the overall relationship between degree_p and etest_p. Hence, we can first conclude that degree percentage might be a significant factor for predicting employability test score, but different field of study might not affect the result of prediction from degree percentage.

This can be proven by the model summary and anova table, where we first see that the model with both degree_p and degree_t included gives a p-value of 7.3556115^{-4} for degree_p , which is significant at 5% level. But both levels of degree_t are not significant even at 10% level, indicating that degree_t might not be a good predictor for etest_p.

We then perform nested test to check if adding degree_t would explain more variability of etest_p, and the p-value provided is not significant (0.759515) at 5% level. Hence, we can conclude that , field of research does not explain much extra variability for etest_p.
